(216, 3, '2012-04-09 18:35:52', '2012-04-09 18:35:52', 'Performance artist John Kelly is that most elusive sort of creator: one that challenges his public and stays true to his principles while managing to sell. His work has garnered both critical and popular acclaim, despite his atypical and potentially disquieting performance style. His longest-running and most famous show (he has dubbed it his "Bolero") is "Paved Paradise," an homage to Joni Mitchell performed in a wig, dress, and full makeup (Levy). The act has been a hit since its debut at the inaugural Wigstock festival in 1985, so much so that Kelly has nearly become defined by it (Levy). People continuously pay good money to watch John Kelly "do Joni," and it''s not only the gay community in the audience: a survey of blogs and comments on Internet sites shows that heterosexuals embrace the idea of the drag show as well, at least when Kelly is the one doing the dragging (<em>John Kelly Performance</em>). It''s a little strange that this should be so. After all, many people might be profoundly perturbed if John Kelly entered their homes as Joni Mitchell or bumped into them on the street wearing lipstick and heels. Yet patrons gladly shell out for theater tickets to watch Kelly perform drag on a stage in front of hundreds of people. How can such behavior be so frowned upon in private yet cheered in public? To attempt to understand this conundrum, we must first determine why drag can both disturb and delight.\n\nIn feminist theorist Judith Butler''s book, <em>Gender Trouble</em>, she argues that our society has developed a "radical dependency" on a "very binary frame [of] thinking about gender" (xxx). We create "ostensible categories" through our system of gender norms, a system which is based on a perceived masculine/feminine dichotomy. Our "codes of purity and taboos" establish what "will and will not be intelligibly human, what will and will not be ''real''": in other words, what will be "normal" (Butler xxv). Through this process, Butler argues that questions of gender become subjected to a black-and-white discourse on "truth or falsity," where societal conventions choose who is assigned "legitimacy" (186, xxv).\n\nDrag, then, inhabits a gray area of the gender spectrum, straddling the line between true and false and even threatening to erase it altogether. When we watch a drag show, we encounter a curious challenge: how do we classify the performer based on our binary model of gender? Drag becomes an odd sort of "double inversion," setting before us two equally plausible yet opposite interpretations of the artist''s gender: the performer could be a man on the outside with a woman inside (a body with an Adam''s apple and testicles is channeling a female spirit), or (s)he could be a woman with a man inside (the feminine exterior in the form of the costume is covering up the masculine body that lies underneath) (Butler 186). These "contradict[ing]" "claims to truth" subvert the entire notion of "truth and falsity" (Butler 186-7). Drag queens blatantly buck the framework of binary gender that society has created (which Butler labels a "preemptive and violent circumscription of reality") and in doing so they expose "the tenuousness of gender" and the circumvention of actuality "performed by gender norms" (Butler xxv).\n\nJeffrey Jerome Cohen, an academic who often concerns himself with entities on the outskirts of our societal boundaries, writes in his essay, "Monster Culture," that beings with "ontological liminality" that hang between spheres of perception and appear to "question binary thinking and introduce a crisis" are (or can be called) "monsters" (6). Cohen''s "monsters" are entities that exist as "disturbing hybrids" outside of the "classificatory ''order of things''" (6). They are "form[s] suspended between forms," just as drag performers are. Given Butler''s analysis of drag as a force that threatens to subvert cultural boundaries, therefore, we may safely label John Kelly and his ilk "monstrous" (Cohen 6) in that they are "third term[s] that problematize the clash of extremes" (that is, terms that do not uphold our notion of a dichotomous and exclusive social order); they are "dangerous" beings that "threaten to smash distinctions" (6).\n\nThrough this discourse between Cohen and Butler, it becomes evident why drag agitates us so. The drag performer represents a direct refutation of all our preconceived binary assumptions about gender, and so can be viewed as a sort of monster. Both Cohen and Butler recognize that, in Cohen''s words, drag queens demand "a radical rethinking of boundary and normality" (6), what Butler calls "a radical shift in one''s notion of the possible and the real (xxiv). This realization that a major revision of "truth" is needed to accurately understand the complexities of gender breeds a cognitive "dissonance" in our logical, compartmentalized minds (Butler 187).\n\nPart of what makes us fear "monsters" is their ability to destroy (villages, cultural frameworks), but their "destructiveness" is really a "deconstructiveness" (Cohen 14). The monster dismantles our artificial categorizations, Cohen says, by showing us that "difference originates in process rather than in fact" (14). Butler comes to a similar conclusion regarding gender specifically, writing that the "naturalized knowledge of gender is, in fact, a changeable and revisable reality" (190, see also xxiv). Through the "double inversion" of drag (the ambiguity of the artist''s identity), "drag implicitly reveals the imitative nature of gender itself" (Butler 186-7). If the performer can essentially "play" a woman, or a man, and thereby become a strange hybrid between the two, it suggests not only that our two distinct gender categories can be mixed at will, but also that all gender identity can be arrived at through acting and imitation. A performance like John Kelly''s recognizes the artifice of the common gender structure even when such "configurations . . . are regularly assumed to be natural and necessary" (Butler 187). The "monster" of drag creates a "revolution in the very logic of meaning" (Cohen 7).\n\nThis revolutionary aspect of drag goes a long way towards explaining why Kelly refers to his performances as "punk" and also why audiences flock to see him partake in a "freakish" act (Levy). Our cognitive dissonance, our aversion to the "monster" (what Cohen would call a sort of fear), is no barrier to our enjoyment of the show—and on some level, it may even enhance it. While watching a drag show, our "bored and repressed" minds are treated to a temporary unshackling, we are "freed to populate the margins" (Cohen 17) of our conceptual landscape with John/Joni. Even if some in Kelly''s audience have no desire to don a dress themselves and start crooning "Big Yellow Taxi," on some level they appreciate and even admire Kelly''s ability to fearlessly challenge their most basic societal assumptions—as a punk rocker, he is sticking it to the man. Butler lends her support to this interpretation, arguing that "part of the pleasure [of drag] . . . is the recognition of a radical contingency between sex and gender" (Butler 187); that is, our love of the performance stems from Kelly''s demonstration that our assumed male/female dichotomy is <em>un</em>natural and<em>un</em>necessary. "We distrust . . . the monster at the same time we envy its freedom," Cohen says, and therein lies the core of our attraction to drag. It is not the cross-dressing itself that we "fear and desire," but the act of liberation that comes with the recognition of gender''s fluidity (Cohen 16). Some may still distrust the practice, or be perturbed by the implications drag holds for our societal codes, yet many are intrigued by the possibility that a performer like John Kelly offers.\n\nCohen provides one way to reconcile the inherent dilemma of the drag show (i.e., how a behavior can be held suspect in society yet lauded on stage): By keeping Kelly removed in a theatrical setting, we allow him a "clearly delimited" and "permanently liminal" space in which to live, just as we do for other "monsters" in Cohen''s conception (17). In this realm we are temporarily treated to escapist fantasies, but we can rest assured that the show will indeed sometime end. The fun of the performance only stops, Cohen says, when the monster threatens to leave its enclosure and obliterate the "thin walls of category and culture" (17). Thus Butler''s recognition that the "giddiness" of a drag show lies in "<em>implicitly reveal[ing] the imitative structure of gender itself</em>," and exposing our own cultural framework as artifice, is only half of the puzzle, because if the same device was used <em>offstage</em> to subvert gender norms the transvestite would be greeted with a profound wariness (187). The key to the appeal of drag to a mass audience is that such subversive, liberating behavior takes place as a "safe expression" of "monstrosity": it is relegated to the stage, where we may play and let our minds wander freely while knowing that we are watching a show.\n\nThis seems to adequately resolve our curious drag paradox, but our interpretation needs revision when John Kelly puts it to the test. Near the end of "Paved Paradise," the performer "suddenly sheds his costume," "stepping out of his role and creating a moment that is strangely profound" (Levy). The audience is "unsettled, affected" by this gesture, yet they often give Kelly a rousing standing ovation (Levy). Why should this moment provoke such an outpouring of approval? After all, every member of the crowd bought a ticket knowing they were going to watch a man do Joni, so why react so overtly when Kelly confirms what they already know? For that matter, what''s "unsettling" about Kelly revealing he''s not a woman—didn''t everyone come to see a dude in a dress? This moment (including Kelly''s gesture and the audience''s reaction to it) is a crucial key to understanding the drag mystery.\n\nBefore addressing the significance of this moment, though, we must acknowledge that John Kelly is extremely good at what he does.<em> The New York Times''</em> Ann Powers captures Kelly''s unique skill in her review of "Paved Paradise," writing "There''s drag, and then there''s transformation through spiritual osmosis," while no less a luminary than Joni Mitchell herself declared that watching John Kelly made her feel like "Huck Finn attending his own funeral . . . I didn''t expect to be so touched" (<em>John Kelly Performance</em>). The fact that Kelly can deliver such a profound out-of-body experience to Mitchell shows that Kelly is not simply putting a caricature before his audience, but rather fully embodying his subject so effectively that even the subject herself is moved. This holds its own implications. Butler might point out that because Kelly''s artificial gender is so convincing, it reveals that "the original identity after which gender fashions itself is an imitation" (188). But I would argue that Kelly''s skill in fact de-emphasizes the "drag" aspect of his show. Through his intense "channeling" of Mitchell, Kelly effectively makes us forget, at least for a time, that it is a man singing (Levy). He leads us into the Cohenian realm of "escapist delight" (Butler''s state of "giddiness") that results from communing with a "monster" in a secure context (17). Kelly becomes an actor, a person bringing life to a role, and if he stays in that mode, the piece is little more than a masculine woman performing. We can let our minds forget for a while that Kelly is a man because he so fully enters his character, and in doing so we take a little of the edge off "Paved Paradise."\n\nHowever, when Kelly removes his wig, we are jarred back out of this forgetfulness. The dramatic reveal is Kelly''s punkiest statement—this<em> is</em> drag, and don''t you forget it. Some may argue that by "revealing" he is a man, Kelly effectively restores order to our fragile system by upholding the "reality" of his masculinity, but I hold that the action is more complex than that. The "unsettled" crowd at this crucial moment is not disturbed because logical categories are being upheld—where''s the danger in that? They are unsettled because Kelly has taken his subversion one step further: through the "device" of shedding his costume (Kelly''s words), the performer can really "mess with people" (Levy).\n\nDrag is artifice, a kind of theater. By calling the act of removing this artifice a "device," Kelly says that even taking his wig off is a staged gesture, that the shedding of the costume and the ostensible restoration of order is just as "put on" as the drag show itself (Levy). The entirety of "Paved Paradise" is "gender performance" (that is, a man acting like a woman), but if becoming a man is part of the performance as well, then how do we know when the acting stops? How do we know when we''re watching something "real?" The answer is that it''s <em>all</em> real, and it''s equally all staged: the reveal in Kelly''s act takes us into the labyrinth of gender with no string to follow back home. Gender becomes, as Butler says, "an imitation without an origin," "neither true nor false" (188, 193).\n\nThis revelation challenges us, it pushes our buttons, yet at the same time its inherent liberation is exhilarating. The audience cheers the heady sense of freedom that comes with stretching the limits we have created for ourselves. In so effectively subverting gender constructs, Kelly takes us all the way to the edge of the cliff, lets our stomach get butterflies as we experience the thrill of looking down. Then he goes one step further by taking off the wig. He shoves us over, yet catches us before we drop, leading to such a rush that we have to cheer. "Paved Paradise" strains our boundaries to their extreme, yet stays <em>just</em> safe enough (as a stage show) to keep its audience from becoming too frightened. John Kelly''s drag is exciting because it is somewhat akin to cognitive bungee-jumping, with trust in the fiction of theater as the cord.\n\n&nbsp;', '"The Giddiness of the Performance": An Investigation of Disturbing, Delightful Drag', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '213-autosave', '', '', '2012-04-09 18:35:52', '2012-04-09 18:35:52', '', 213, 'http://digital.lampdev.columbia.edu/morningsidereview/?p=216', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(218, 5, '2011-12-17 05:12:15', '2011-12-17 05:12:15', '“I don’t think I learned anything new about women ... but to see it as a collection ... it’s the first time that women have ambition, that they mind ... what I saw in those first shoots was powerful...it was very emotional.”\r\n—Annie Leibovitz on her 1999 book of portraits, <em>Women</em>\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_49" align="alignright" width="330" caption="Bene_E1_clip_image002"]<img class="size-full wp-image-49 " title="Bene_E1_clip_image002" src="http://digital.lampdev.columbia.edu/morningsidereview/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/Bene_E1_clip_image002.jpg" alt="Bene_E1_clip_image002" width="330" height="224" />[/caption]\r\n\r\nCarly Fiorina, the former President and CEO of Hewlett Packard, catches my eye. She is featured in deep shadow at the rear of what looks to be a small corporate jet. She sits alone on the leather seat, cross-legged, and stares off into the distance past the camera, seemingly with no knowledge of its presence. I am compelled by the moment’s quiet intimacy; the photograph offers the illusion of reality, as opposed to a shot for which Fiorina struck a pose. A slight blue tint glazes the photo but there is no movement, no other living being. The focus is Fiorina and her stoic presence; deep in thought, she is neither smiling nor frowning. The image is from a series of over 200 portraits of American women published together in 1999 by photographer Annie Leibovitz. As I thumb through the large book, I am puzzled and intrigued by Leibovitz’s project: what, if anything, is she up to? Is this yet another coffee-table book of glossy photographs loosely strung together by a sweeping thesis or a retrospective with greater ambitions? What is so compelling about Fiorina’s representation?\r\n\r\nIn her essay entitled “In Our Glory: Photography and Black Life,” bell hooks explores photography and image-making as powerful means of representation. She explicitly defines “representation” as “control over images” (57). The central, primary document she uses to explore this idea is a snapshot of her father, entitled “In his glory” (53). She is surprised by the bold openness with which “he faces the camera”: this was an image of a black man in his own context. It seems to me that hooks’ definition of representation acknowledges an entire spectrum of control: first, an image’s subject and content, but also the framing of that image, control over the access of an image, the nature of its presentation and context, and so on. Hooks argues that insofar as we are able to control how others see us, photography is always subjective. This feature of constructing personal identity is linked to hooks’ conclusion that photography also reflects the community. As a black woman, she characterizes the array of photographs hung on her grandmother’s walls as empowering and a reflection of her community’s visual complexity. Significantly, these photographs, which reflected her community, were made by members of her community. Photography’s subjectivity can be understood from the perspective of the viewer of the image, but also its maker. Through hooks’ observations about representation, Leibovitz emerges as a figure with intent, with awareness of the representation of her subject. She exercises control over her images, which take on new significance.\r\n\r\nLeibovitz has said that completing the book did not change her idea of what it meant to be a woman. But from the outside looking in, she said it was the first time that women “have [had] ambition, that they mind.” Hooks speaks to this tension as the ongoing struggle between “how we see ourselves” and “how others see us” (57); for Leibovitz perhaps the distinction is between “how women see themselves” and “how society sees them.” Each case involves a subjugated community whose understanding of itself is at odds with that of an “other.” But hooks’ focus is racial oppression. She calls for an intervention in which black image production serves as a significant means of self-representation. The personal photographs on her grandmother’s wall are, for her, an important departure from white control over black images; these were images of a segregated community produced from within that community. Still, despite hooks’ claim that racist images were being countered by true-to-life images, self-representation has little to do with presenting a truer sense of reality (59). The power of self-representation is such that people can always control how others view them—no representation is any more “real” than another. In this way, the essay sheds light on Leibovitz’s work: as a woman photographing women, she uses self-representation as a means of challenging traditional depictions of women made by men, or the “others” outside her community.\r\n\r\nMidway through her investigation, hooks introduces Roger Wilkins’ theory that the power over representation allows one to “define reality ... manage perceptions and ... arrange politics and culture to reinforce those definitions” (58). This is also an appropriate definition for “authorship,” despite the fact that hooks does not use the word explicitly. Through this idea of photographer as author, hooks explores the camera as “a political instrument” (60). She asserts that much of the black liberation movement can be seen as a “struggle over images” in which society’s most prevalent representations of blacks were controlled by persons outside the black community (57). It is an argument which (when taken with Leibovitz''s portraits) also makes sense in the context of the women’s rights movement. When hooks’ theory is applied to Leibovitz’s photography, her images become a means of challenging and resisting the misrepresentation of women. While Leibovitz’s intent may be clearer through hooks’ essay, we must return to the photographs themselves in order to examine if and how she manages to achieve her objective.\r\nAs a spectator viewing the image of Carly Fiorina, I am struck by a paradox: is this a private moment of content, self-assuredness, or a solemn portrait of a person struck by the solitude of power? The tone here is neither blatantly celebratory nor somber. Visually, Fiorina is isolated and her body language could be interpreted as further signs of that solitariness: her legs are crossed, she is turned into herself, her hands rest just above her knees. The framing of the scene around the plane’s rear compartment captures a world physically closing in around her. On the other hand, that very arch of the plane, which closes her off from the outside world, also acts as a lens, which draws the viewer''s attention inward. Are we meant to be drawn towards Fiorina’s confidence and dignified comfort in this world? hooks might interpret this ambiguity as a kind of visual resistance that substitutes female archetypes with representations of individuality. Leibovitz’s representation intentionally poses questions that cannot be answered in any narrow sense. For hooks, the “dehumanization” of blacks as caricatures or cartoon-like figures on saltshakers and cookie jars could only be challenged through the presence of humanity in the photos from her childhood (59). Self-representation offered a “sense of self and identity” (63). The paradox, which I confronted in the image of Carly Fiorina, is a feature of her representation. Leibovitz challenges the archetype of “a woman in power” by framing the photo in such a way as to prevent Fiorina’s state from being singularly definable. She is more than “a woman,” more than “a powerful woman;” here, Fiorina does not fit into a mold because she is instead represented as a living, breathing individual. She has identity separate from her distinction as a woman, a sense of self.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_48" align="alignright" width="378" caption="Bene_E1_clip_image004"]<img class="size-full wp-image-48 " title="Bene_E1_clip_image004" src="http://digital.lampdev.columbia.edu/morningsidereview/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/Bene_E1_clip_image004.jpg" alt="Bene_E1_clip_image004" width="378" height="243" />[/caption]\r\n\r\nLeibovitz’s project presents itself as a unique opportunity to challenge through representation. In denying the spectator''s ability to define in exclusive terms, Leibovitz is acutely aware of the power of representation, or the control over images. A photograph of Supreme Court Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Sandra Day O’Connor appears in the latter half of the book. Their faces are familiar but their status is elevated, regal in their judicial robes. For me, this photograph involves a unique acknowledgment of traditional, archetypal representations of women: that they are presented to be looked at. They are the objects of our gaze. Here, Ginsburg and O’Connor look out at us. Leibovitz’s mise-en-scène evokes a particular openness. Contrary to the portrait of Carly Fiorina, this environment is well lit, even bright. The room is not claustrophobic but spacious and elongated, actually extending beyond the frame. The table itself has an open, reflective quality. The two women turn out to face us but their unflinching strength suggests they expect something in return. And if we have nothing to say to them, they certainly seem prepared to speak to us. They will not merely accept our passive gaze. They do, however, seem to accept the gaze of the man featured in the portrait above them. The portrait’s gold-frame is the most striking hue in the photograph. Is this looming presence related to the struggle over sexism which itself still overhangs America’s political-judicial system? Or is their disregard for the portrait’s presence more significant? Are they content or burdened or both?\r\n\r\nJust as hooks describes her father as one who “exerted control over [her family’s] images,” Leibovitz’s authorship is significant. In the first photograph she actively crafted a presentation of Carly Fiorina that challenges sexist archetypes. She composes a purposefully ambiguous tableau, promoting conflicting observations that emphasized Fiorina’s individuality. In this second image, Leibovitz’s purpose-driven composition has less to do with paradox; instead the viewer is struck by the glaring, unmistakable presence of the man in the portrait, as he stares down over the two justices. It is difficult to ignore the collision between his presence and the women below; at the very least, Leibovitz compels us to acknowledge the gender distinction. As photographer and author, Leibovitz actively selected the setting, the costumes, the lighting, and the pose. hooks remarks that the black community’s access to image-making was liberating, in part, because “subjects [could be] positioned according to individual desire” (59). Her observations suggest that the composition of this image and the specific choices related to that composition are not coincidental but reflect Leibovitz’s specific intent. She positions these two particular women below that particular portrait deliberately in order to elicit a response. Applying hooks’ ideas, it can said that Leibovitz “resist[s] misrepresentation” by producing “alternative images” (60). The man in the portrait takes on a role quite different from his traditional cultural representation. Here, through Leibovitz’s lens, he represents men, as an entire community, and the ever-present sexist subordination of women (even those who hold the country’s highest positions of power). And yet, Ginsburg and O’Connor seem undeterred by this man’s presence; they are not victims of his glance but neither are they detached from it.\r\n\r\nhooks accounts for the coexistence of these opposing possibilities (the kind that also arise in the image of Fiorina) as she comments on images from her childhood: “In opposition to colonizing socialization, internalized racism, these walls [of photographs] announced our visual complexity” (61). Again, Leibovitz embraces and calls visual attention to the complexity of the individual; her representation defies narrow definition. The breadth of her subject and title of her book, <em>Women</em>, is playful. As an image-maker with specific intent, her representations of women exploit the expectation that her subject is a singular, identifiable entity. Her portraits of women are multidimensional in themselves, presented in the context of hundreds of other women with diverse backgrounds and experiences. Her subject is women as a category that defies categorization. v\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'What is She Up To?: Annie Leibovitz and the Politics of Representation', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'what-is-she-up-to-annie-leibovitz-and-the-politics-of-representation', '', '', '2012-03-23 16:00:10', '2012-03-23 16:00:10', '', 0, 'http://digital.lampdev.columbia.edu/morningsidereview/?post_type=essay&#038;p=218', 0, 'essay', '', 0),
