(364, 2, '2012-02-07 23:46:13', '2012-02-07 23:46:13', '<strong>[NOTE: Text about TMR and its essays. Messages need to be archived.]</strong>\r\n\r\nDear Readers,\r\n\r\nThe essayist Randolph Bourne--a leftist intellectual and graduate of Columbia University''s class of 1905(?) rejected the possibility of young people writing meaningful essays. “The youthful essayist,” he wrote in the month before his death in 1918, “is afraid you will think he is unsophisticated, while the middle-aged doesn’t much care if you do. […] The youthful essayist usually develops into the professional anecdotalist, with an active mind that is harnessed up to no real thinking but can only stream off from itself a futile current of incident” (506). This is a strange—even a disheartening—sentiment to hear from Bourne, an essayist who never made it to sanguine middle age himself. He was writing, however, about the "light essay," a form of the essay that was epitomized by such well known writers as Charles Lamb. But Bourne, while insightful about many things, including the dangers of American thinkers tacitly approving the first World War, because they did not sufficiently consider what it asked us to rethink about democracy itself, was wrong about the essay. And Bourne also here fails to mention his own first attempts to do "real thinking" in essays in the Columbia Monthly, including articles on X, Y, and Z. If Bourne were a first year student at Columbia today, I would guess that he would be a prolific blogger, and would seek out as many opportunities for explorations of his ideas in public as he could.\r\n\r\nTo write an essay to an imagined (and actual) audience of smart readers who are not familiar with the particulars of the issues that concern oneself, but who can become interested by them is no small feat. To write both persuasively, thoughtfully, responsibly about questions about contemporary topics ranging from use of placebos trials to the complexity of drag performance, or the lasting effects of DADT despite its revocation situates the student writer as a person who can and should speak/write publicly on these issues--not to simply express his or her opinions, but to begin the heady process of entering into an existing intellectual conversation and exchange of ideas.\r\n\r\nThere is a genre called the essay which is particularly flexible and able to accomodate a wide range of subjects, writerly stances, aesthetic experiments and argumentative strategies. It is the essay''s diversity that this publication showcases and celebrates, although we do emphasize essays that make their arguments rather more explicitly than those on the more implicit and elliptical end of the spectrum.\r\n\r\nI am proud and fascinated of the work that students who are new to this form of writing have been able to accomplish with one semester''s worth of hard study of the genre''s requirements. And of all of what essay asks, it most demands that its writers show up and make their thinking visible to others on the page. This is no solipsistic act--the ideas are there because they are meaningful and could be meaningful to others.\r\n\r\nThe Core curriculum at Columbia includes many famous essayists on its curriculum, including both Michel de Montaigne and Francis Bacon. How fitting then that as students begin their study here that they might find a space to conduct their own experiments in thinking in the only course at Columbia that is required of all first year students: University Writing.\r\n\r\nAs you consider the essays in this journal, you might find it interesting to see how even the most timely of or students'' arguments--that respond to key controversies of their day--the Jessica Lynch story, the Borat movie, the RiceTek patenting case feature ideas that are of lasting interest and merit. This is why essays in the world continue to be read long after their timeliness--their kairotic appeals--diminish: because in the presence of a thinker working carefully to craft an idea about a text well known or just discovered, we feel the thrill of a moment of invention. In essays these moments are not preserved or fixed but recreated, and the force of the best essays by writers regardless of their age is that of the click--the idea that was nascent and only dimmly detected made visible and sharable with others. The art of the essay is alive and well at Columbia and we look forward to many more volumes of The Morningside Review to show us of what new essaysists in our midsts can contribute to the form.\r\n\r\nWith all best wishes,\r\n\r\n<a href="http://digital.lampdev.columbia.edu/morningsidereview/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/NBWsig.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-440" title="NBW signature" src="http://digital.lampdev.columbia.edu/morningsidereview/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/NBWsig-300x55.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="55" /></a>\r\nNicole B. Wallack, PhD\r\nDirector, Undergraduate Writing Program', 'From the Director', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'from-the-director', '', '', '2012-02-28 17:37:13', '2012-02-28 17:37:13', '', 129, 'http://digital.lampdev.columbia.edu/morningsidereview/?page_id=364', 0, 'page', '', 0),
